<subSubSection id="1585B48EDD095D414AF1FF51FBF30D13" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD095D414AF1FF51FF3C08AD" blockId="14.[131,777,216,2028]" box="[132,240,216,242]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">FINDINGS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD095D414AF1FF7EFD6E092C" blockId="14.[131,777,216,2028]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
The description by Poiret is based on a specimen in the collection of Jussieu. Consequently, since it is extant, this must be considered the 
<typeStatus id="822459A7DD095D414BEAFEBEFDCF090C" box="[415,515,311,337]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<collectionCode id="3B8E7FC0DD095D414862FEBEFDEB090C" box="[535,551,311,337]" country="France" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15763" name="Museum National d' Histoire Naturelle, Paris (MNHN) - Vascular Plants" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" type="Herbarium">P</collectionCode>
00320321). As was typical in that era, it only consists of a floricane.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD095D414AEEFEFEFCCE0AB2" blockId="14.[131,777,216,2028]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
This name was not used for any American bramble until Bailey received a photo of it from 
<collectionCode id="3B8E7FC0DD095D414860FE1EFDFE09EC" box="[533,562,407,433]" country="Germany" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15637" name="Botanische Staatssammlung München" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" type="Herbarium">M</collectionCode>
. 
<collectionCode id="3B8E7FC0DD095D414843FE1EFD8609EC" box="[566,586,407,433]" country="Netherlands" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15678" name="Nationaal Herbarium Nederland, Leiden University branch" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" type="Herbarium">L</collectionCode>
. Fernald (
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D4148B7FE1FFF37098C" author="BAILEY L. H." pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="591 - 835" refId="ref16395" refString="BAILEY L. H. 1945. - Rubus in North America. Eubatus. Arguti. Gentes Herbarum 5: 591 - 835. https: // hdl. handle. net / 2027 / uc 1.31210001328085" type="journal article" year="1945">Bailey 1945: 704</bibRefCitation>
) and identified it with plants that he found at many locations in the eastern 
<collectingCountry id="2588A795DD095D414BA0FE5FFDA609AD" box="[469,618,470,496]" name="United States of America" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">United States</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D41480FFE5FFF200A4D" author="BAILEY L. H." pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="591 - 835" refId="ref16395" refString="BAILEY L. H. 1945. - Rubus in North America. Eubatus. Arguti. Gentes Herbarum 5: 591 - 835. https: // hdl. handle. net / 2027 / uc 1.31210001328085" type="journal article" year="1945">Bailey 1945: 702-704</bibRefCitation>
). Consequently, 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414BC6FE7EFDAB0A4D" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[435,615,502,528]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414BC6FE7EFDAB0A4D" box="[435,615,502,528]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
suddenly became a rather common species. 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D414B96FD9FFD7F0A6C" author="BAILEY L. H." box="[483,691,534,561]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="591 - 835" refId="ref16395" refString="BAILEY L. H. 1945. - Rubus in North America. Eubatus. Arguti. Gentes Herbarum 5: 591 - 835. https: // hdl. handle. net / 2027 / uc 1.31210001328085" type="journal article" year="1945">Bailey (1945: 699)</bibRefCitation>
treated 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414AF1FDBEFEE30A0D" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[132,303,566,592]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414AF1FDBEFEE30A0D" box="[132,303,566,592]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a member of the 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D41487BFDBFFD9F0A0D" box="[526,595,566,592]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Arguti</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D414814FDBFFF740A2C" author="FERNALD M. L." pageId="14" pageNumber="79" refId="ref17495" refString="FERNALD M. L. 1950. - Gray's Manual of Botany. 8 TH ed. American Book Co., New York, 1632 p." type="book" year="1950">Fernald (1950: 861)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D414A83FDDFFDDF0A2C" author="DAVIS H. A. &amp; FULLER A. M. &amp; DAVIS T." box="[246,531,598,625]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="235 - 266" refId="ref17164" refString="DAVIS H. A., FULLER A. M. &amp; DAVIS T. 1969 b. - Contributions toward the Revision of the Eubati of Eastern North America. V. Arguti. Castanea 34 (3): 235 - 266. https: // www. jstor. org / stable / 4032358" type="journal article" year="1969">
Davis 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414B48FDDEFEB80A2D" box="[317,372,598,624]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">et al.</emphasis>
(1969b: 262)
</bibRefCitation>
followed him in that regard. Notably, 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D414B33FDFFFDDE0ACD" author="ALICE L. A. &amp; GOLDMAN D. H. &amp; MACKLIN J. A. &amp; MOORE G." box="[326,530,630,656]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" refId="ref16022" refString="ALICE L. A., GOLDMAN D. H., MACKLIN J. A., &amp; MOORE G. 2014. - Rubus (Rosaceae) in Flora of North America North of Mexico. Vol. 9. Oxford University Press, New York: 28 - 56." type="book" year="2014">
Alice 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414BF0FDFEFE710ACD" box="[389,445,630,656]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">et al.</emphasis>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
treated essentially all members of section 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414B14FD1FFE6A0AED" box="[353,422,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Arguti</emphasis>
under this name, believing it to be the oldest name for the pubescent, highbush blackberries lacking stipitate glands, which comprise this section.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD095D414AEEFD7FFEA90C33" blockId="14.[131,777,216,2028]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
However, Bailey based his identification only on a photo, one of insufficient resolution to notice the finest details. Thierry Deroin (
<collectionCode id="3B8E7FC0DD095D414B3EFCBCFE910B12" box="[331,349,821,847]" country="France" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15763" name="Museum National d' Histoire Naturelle, Paris (MNHN) - Vascular Plants" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" type="Herbarium">P</collectionCode>
) checked Poiret’s 
<typeStatus id="822459A7DD095D414840FCBFFDAA0B0D" box="[565,614,822,848]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">type</typeStatus>
carefully and noted that it bears very short stipitate glands on its pedicels and also some on the inflorescence axis, along with a few longer stipitate glands. This observation was confirmed by high-resolution photos that he sent to us. Consequently, the 
<typeStatus id="822459A7DD095D414AC7FC5CFF2E0BB2" box="[178,226,981,1007]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">type</typeStatus>
does not belong to the 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414B87FC5CFDFB0BB2" box="[498,567,981,1007]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Arguti</emphasis>
but instead to the 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414AF3FC7DFED70C53" box="[134,283,1012,1038]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Alleghenienses</emphasis>
. In sharp contrast, 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D414877FC7DFD560C52" author="BAILEY L. H." box="[514,666,1012,1039]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="591 - 835" refId="ref16395" refString="BAILEY L. H. 1945. - Rubus in North America. Eubatus. Arguti. Gentes Herbarum 5: 591 - 835. https: // hdl. handle. net / 2027 / uc 1.31210001328085" type="journal article" year="1945">Bailey (1945)</bibRefCitation>
made no mention of any glandular trichomes in his detailed description of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414AA9FBBCFE440C13" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[220,392,1076,1102]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414AA9FBBCFE440C13" box="[220,392,1076,1102]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, consistent with his placement of it within the 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414B6DFBDDFEAD0C33" box="[280,353,1108,1134]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Arguti</emphasis>
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414B14FBDDFEA90C33" box="[353,357,1108,1134]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD095D414AEEFBFDFCC40E71" blockId="14.[131,777,216,2028]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
So, in a single publication, 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D414BB4FBFDFD990CD2" author="POIRET J. L. M." box="[449,597,1140,1167]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" refId="ref18455" refString="POIRET J. L. M. 1804. - Encyclopedie methodique. Botanique. Vol. 6. Agasse, Paris, 786 p. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 824" type="book" year="1804">Poiret (1804)</bibRefCitation>
named two species that fall within the 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414BE6FB1DFDE40CF3" box="[403,552,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Alleghenienses</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414842FB1CFD780CF3" baseAuthorityName="Poiret" baseAuthorityYear="1804" box="[567,692,1172,1198]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vulpinus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414842FB1CFD780CF3" box="[567,692,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. vulpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which clearly displays the stipitate glands that are a key character of that section and otherwise conforms to the plant widely known as 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414A89FB7DFE600D50" baseAuthorityName="Porter" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[252,428,1267,1293]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="allegheniensis">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414A89FB7DFE600D50" box="[252,428,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. allegheniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414B86FB7DFD6C0D50" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[499,672,1267,1293]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414B86FB7DFD6C0D50" box="[499,672,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with its sparse glandularity less typical of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414B8BFA9DFD610D70" baseAuthorityName="Porter" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[510,685,1299,1325]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="allegheniensis">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414B8BFA9DFD610D70" box="[510,685,1299,1325]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. allegheniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Such a plant might even represent an intersectional hybrid or be an earlier name for 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414B10FADDFDA90D30" authority="L. H. Bailey." authorityName="L. H. Bailey." box="[357,613,1363,1390]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="abactus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414B10FADDFE190D30" box="[357,469,1363,1389]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. abactus</emphasis>
L.H. Bailey.
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D41481BFADAFCC40D30" box="[622,776,1363,1389]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="abactus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D41481BFADAFCC40D30" box="[622,776,1363,1389]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Rubus abactus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been treated as a close ally of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D41487CFAFDFD7B0DD0" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[521,695,1395,1421]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D41487CFAFDFD7B0DD0" box="[521,695,1395,1421]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
within the 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414AC5FA1AFF390DF0" box="[176,245,1427,1453]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Arguti</emphasis>
(keying out in the same couplet in 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D4148FFFA1AFF000D90" author="DAVIS H. A. &amp; FULLER A. M. &amp; DAVIS T." pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="235 - 266" refId="ref17164" refString="DAVIS H. A., FULLER A. M. &amp; DAVIS T. 1969 b. - Contributions toward the Revision of the Eubati of Eastern North America. V. Arguti. Castanea 34 (3): 235 - 266. https: // www. jstor. org / stable / 4032358" type="journal article" year="1969">
Davis 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D4148A4FA1DFCCB0DF0" box="[721,775,1427,1453]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">et al.</emphasis>
1969b
</bibRefCitation>
), but a careful examination of the 
<typeStatus id="822459A7DD095D41483DFA3AFDB40D90" box="[584,632,1459,1485]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D4148ECFA3DFCC90D90" box="[665,773,1459,1485]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="abactus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D4148ECFA3DFCC90D90" box="[665,773,1459,1485]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. abactus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
revealed that it also bears short stipitate glands on its pedicels, along with a few longer stipitate glands on its inflorescence axis, as well as having coarser, jagged leaf serrations.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD095D414AEEF9BBFD260FB6" blockId="14.[131,777,216,2028]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
If the 
<typeStatus id="822459A7DD095D414A96F9BAFEDF0E10" box="[227,275,1587,1613]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414B4BF9BAFE200E11" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[318,492,1586,1612]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414B4BF9BAFE200E11" box="[318,492,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were more complete, we might be able to place 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414BFAF9DAFDCC0E31" box="[399,512,1618,1644]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="abactus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414BFAF9DAFDCC0E31" box="[399,512,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. abactus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in synonymy under it, but there are at least two other options that cannot be fully evaluated without access to both well-developed primocane and floricane samples of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414BFBF93AFDFA0E91" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[398,566,1714,1740]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414BFBF93AFDFA0E91" box="[398,566,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. First, it is possible that the 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414A93F95AFE5F0EB1" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[230,403,1746,1772]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414A93F95AFE5F0EB1" box="[230,403,1746,1772]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus id="822459A7DD095D414BEEF95BFE070EB1" box="[411,459,1746,1772]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">type</typeStatus>
represents a weak specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414AD5F97AFE810F51" baseAuthorityName="Porter" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[160,333,1778,1804]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="allegheniensis">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414AD5F97AFE810F51" box="[160,333,1778,1804]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. allegheniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Under suboptimal growing conditions, 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414AF6F89BFEFE0F71" baseAuthorityName="Porter" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[131,306,1810,1836]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="allegheniensis">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414AF6F89BFEFE0F71" box="[131,306,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. allegheniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can produce smaller, weaker racemes that are atypical and may display few stipitate glands. Alternatively, in contrast to many apomictic North American blackberries, 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414B62F8FBFE0F0FD6" baseAuthorityName="Porter" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[279,451,1905,1931]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="allegheniensis">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414B62F8FBFE0F0FD6" box="[279,451,1905,1931]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. allegheniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is typically sexual (
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D4148EDF8F8FF3A0FF6" author="AALDERS L. E. &amp; HALL I. V." pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="528 - 532" refId="ref15870" refString="AALDERS L. E. &amp; HALL I. V. 1966. - A cytotaxonomic survey of the native blackberries of Nova Scotia. Canadian Journal of Genetics and Cytology 8: 528 - 532. https: // doi. org / 10.1139 / g 66 - 063" type="journal article" year="1966">Aalders &amp; Hall 1966</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D414B70F818FE710FF6" author="THOMPSON M. M." box="[261,445,1937,1963]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="128 - 164" refId="ref19111" refString="THOMPSON M. M. 1997. - Survey of chromosome numbers in Rubus (Rosaceae: Rosoideae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 84: 128 - 164. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 2399958" type="journal article" year="1997">Thompson 1997</bibRefCitation>
) with the ability to hybridize with other sympatric taxa. If such hybrids involve 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D4148CEF838FCCC0F96" box="[699,768,1969,1995]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Arguti</emphasis>
, the progeny could present intermediate characteristics.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD095D414931FF5EFA590B72" blockId="14.[811,1457,215,1358]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
If one takes a very broad view of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414ED1FF51FA9C08AC" baseAuthorityName="Porter" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[1188,1360,215,241]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="allegheniensis">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414ED1FF51FA9C08AC" box="[1188,1360,215,241]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. allegheniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with its considerable variation generated by being primarily a sexual diploid (
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D4149FCFE9EFBAB096C" author="AALDERS L. E. &amp; HALL I. V." box="[905,1127,279,305]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="528 - 532" refId="ref15870" refString="AALDERS L. E. &amp; HALL I. V. 1966. - A cytotaxonomic survey of the native blackberries of Nova Scotia. Canadian Journal of Genetics and Cytology 8: 528 - 532. https: // doi. org / 10.1139 / g 66 - 063" type="journal article" year="1966">Aalders &amp; Hall 1966</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D414E06FE9EFAEA096C" author="THOMPSON M. M." box="[1139,1318,279,305]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="128 - 164" refId="ref19111" refString="THOMPSON M. M. 1997. - Survey of chromosome numbers in Rubus (Rosaceae: Rosoideae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 84: 128 - 164. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 2399958" type="journal article" year="1997">Thompson 1997</bibRefCitation>
), potentially either of Poiret’s names from the 1804 publication could be selected for designating the correct name. However, there are two strong arguments to select 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414ECFFEFEFAFF09CC" baseAuthorityName="Poiret" baseAuthorityYear="1804" box="[1210,1331,375,401]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vulpinus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414ECFFEFEFAFF09CC" box="[1210,1331,375,401]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. vulpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. First, it is a typical representative of the species, while 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414F69FE1EFC80098D" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414F69FE1EFC80098D" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is marginal by virtue of its ambiguous trait expression. Second, the name 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D41498EFE5EFB6A09AD" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[1019,1190,470,496]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D41498EFE5EFB6A09AD" box="[1019,1190,470,496]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been in wide use in eastern North America since 1945 for non-glandular highbush blackberries, and its selection would cause considerable confusion if it would be applied to a common species in the same region, while 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414E73FDDEFB4C0A2D" baseAuthorityName="Poiret" baseAuthorityYear="1804" box="[1030,1152,598,624]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vulpinus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414E73FDDEFB4C0A2D" box="[1030,1152,598,624]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. vulpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has never been so used. So 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D41495BFDFEFC6B0ACD" baseAuthorityName="Poiret" baseAuthorityYear="1804" box="[814,935,630,656]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vulpinus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D41495BFDFEFC6B0ACD" box="[814,935,630,656]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. vulpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be indicated as the correct name for the taxon which has long been called 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414EDAFD1FFC5F0A8D" authority="Porter. However" authorityName="Porter. However" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="allegheniensis">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414EDAFD1FFA920AED" box="[1199,1374,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. allegheniensis</emphasis>
Porter. However
</taxonomicName>
, because the name 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414E01FD3FFAEA0A92" box="[1140,1318,693,719]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="allegheniensis">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414E01FD3FFAEA0A92" box="[1140,1318,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. allegheniensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been in use for a long time for a very common species, one which is also widely cultivated, a change of name is not desirable. Thus, we plan to submit a proposal for its conservation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD095D414931FCBFFA5B0B92" blockId="14.[811,1457,215,1358]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
Because of its glandular character, 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414EB9FCBFFABB0B12" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[1228,1399,821,847]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414EB9FCBFFABB0B12" box="[1228,1399,821,847]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not belong to the 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D41498AFCDCFB8E0B32" box="[1023,1090,853,879]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Arguti</emphasis>
. Consequently, if the 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414F36FCDCFA4B0B32" box="[1347,1415,853,879]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Arguti</emphasis>
are considered as one species, asAlice 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414ED5FCFFFB1F0BD2" box="[1184,1235,885,911]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">et al.</emphasis>
(2014) did, the correct name of that species would be 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414ED2FC1FFA9D0BF2" authority="Link" authorityName="Link (Link" authorityYear="1822" box="[1191,1361,917,943]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414ED2FC1FFADF0BF2" box="[1191,1299,918,943]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. argutus</emphasis>
Link
</taxonomicName>
, because this is the oldest of the legitimate names in that section.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD095D414931FC5CFBF30D13" blockId="14.[811,1457,215,1358]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">
<collectionCode id="3B8E7FC0DD095D414931FC5CFC990BB2" box="[836,853,981,1007]" country="USA" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15406" name="Harvard University - Arnold Arboretum" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" type="Herbarium">A</collectionCode>
subsequent question is what must be the correct name of the taxon which was called 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414EFAFC7CFAF30C53" authorityName="Poir. (Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[1167,1343,1012,1038]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414EFAFC7CFAF30C53" box="[1167,1343,1012,1038]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Bailey and later authors who followed him. Neither 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D414F6CFB9DFA630C72" author="BAILEY L. H." box="[1305,1455,1044,1071]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="591 - 835" refId="ref16395" refString="BAILEY L. H. 1945. - Rubus in North America. Eubatus. Arguti. Gentes Herbarum 5: 591 - 835. https: // hdl. handle. net / 2027 / uc 1.31210001328085" type="journal article" year="1945">Bailey (1945)</bibRefCitation>
nor 
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D41492EFBBDFBFB0C12" author="DAVIS H. A. &amp; FULLER A. M. &amp; DAVIS T." box="[859,1079,1076,1103]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="235 - 266" refId="ref17164" refString="DAVIS H. A., FULLER A. M. &amp; DAVIS T. 1969 b. - Contributions toward the Revision of the Eubati of Eastern North America. V. Arguti. Castanea 34 (3): 235 - 266. https: // www. jstor. org / stable / 4032358" type="journal article" year="1969">
Davis 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D4149D4FBBCFC1A0C13" box="[929,982,1076,1102]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">et al.</emphasis>
(1969b)
</bibRefCitation>
mentioned any synonym and we, too, could not find one. Consequently, a new name must be given to it. In order to avoid any further confusion, we describe this taxon as a new species of section 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414F4EFB1DFAB30CF3" box="[1339,1407,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Arguti</emphasis>
and not as a new name for 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414E46FB3CFC9E0CB3" authority="sensu L. H. Bailey. We" authorityName="L. H. Bailey. We" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pensilvanicus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414E46FB3CFB120C93" box="[1075,1246,1204,1230]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">R. pensilvanicus</emphasis>
sensu L.H. Bailey. We
</taxonomicName>
chose the name 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D414E71FB5DFB550CB3" authority="Beek &amp; Widrlechner, 2021" authorityName="A. Beek &amp; M. P. Widrlechner" authorityYear="2021" box="[1028,1177,1236,1262]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="revealii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D414E71FB5DFB550CB3" box="[1028,1177,1236,1262]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Rubus revealii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="74D8866CDD095D414ED5FB5DFB380CB3" box="[1184,1268,1236,1262]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
to honor the late James Reveal (
<bibRefCitation id="390E9AF4DD095D4149B9FB7AFB9C0D53" author="MILLER J. S." box="[972,1104,1267,1294]" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" pagination="282 - 286" refId="ref18172" refString="MILLER J. S. 2015. - In memoriam. James L. Reveal (1941 - 2015). Rhodora 117: 282 - 286. https: // doi. org / 10.3119 / 0035 - 4902 - 117.970. 282" type="journal article" year="2015">Miller 2015</bibRefCitation>
), who contributed much to the knowledge of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD095D4149BEFA9AFBC70D70" box="[971,1035,1299,1325]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="14" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD095D4149BEFA9AFBC70D70" box="[971,1035,1299,1325]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="79">Rubus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, not only of its American species but also its infrageneric taxa.
</paragraph>
